Setup: three custom fields + one validation rule

On Account:

Field	Type	Purpose
Flow_Stamp__c	Text(255)	written by the before-save flow
Trigger_Stamp__c	Text(255)	appended by each before-trigger pass
After_Flow_Stamp__c	Text(255)	written by the after-save flow

Validation rule Trace_Rating_Guard:

AND( ISPICKVAL(Rating, 'Hot'), ISBLANK(Description) )

Error message: Hot accounts need a Description. — deliberately easy to trip so you can watch where the save aborts.

******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

The trace helper

Everything logs at LoggingLevel.ERROR so the lines survive even if you drop Apex Code to ERROR level, and they're trivially greppable.

public class ExecTrace {

    private static Integer seq = 0;
    public  static Integer saveDepth = 0;

    public static void mark(String context, Integer rows) {
        seq++;
        System.debug(LoggingLevel.ERROR, String.format(
            '### [{0}] {1} | depth={2} | rows={3} | SOQL={4}/{5} DML={6}/{7} CPU={8}ms',
            new List<String>{
                String.valueOf(seq),
                context,
                String.valueOf(saveDepth),
                String.valueOf(rows),
                String.valueOf(Limits.getQueries()),
                String.valueOf(Limits.getLimitQueries()),
                String.valueOf(Limits.getDmlStatements()),
                String.valueOf(Limits.getLimitDmlStatements()),
                String.valueOf(Limits.getCpuTime())
            }
        ));
    }

    public static void note(String msg) {
        System.debug(LoggingLevel.ERROR, '###     ' + msg);
    }
}

The limit counters are the important part — they make visible that recursion shares one budget.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The trigger
apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (
    before insert, before update, before delete,
    after  insert, after  update, after  delete, after undelete
) {
    Boolean isSaveEntry = Trigger.isBefore && (Trigger.isInsert || Trigger.isUpdate);
    Boolean isSaveExit  = Trigger.isAfter  && (Trigger.isInsert || Trigger.isUpdate);

    if (isSaveEntry) ExecTrace.saveDepth++;

    ExecTrace.mark(String.valueOf(Trigger.operationType), Trigger.size);

    AccountTriggerHandler.route();

    if (isSaveExit) ExecTrace.saveDepth--;
}

saveDepth is a manual counter — Salesforce exposes no Trigger.depth. Increment on the before-context (first thing in a save), decrement on the after-context (last thing). Delete contexts are left alone.

The handler

public with sharing class AccountTriggerHandler {

    public static void route() {
        switch on Trigger.operationType {
            when BEFORE_INSERT { stamp(Trigger.new, 'BI'); }
            when BEFORE_UPDATE { stamp(Trigger.new, 'BU'); }
            when AFTER_INSERT  { observe(Trigger.new); }
            when AFTER_UPDATE  { observe(Trigger.new); }
            when else          { ExecTrace.note('no-op context'); }
        }
    }

    private static void stamp(List<Account> accts, String tag) {
        for (Account a : accts) {
            // ← the proof: can the trigger already see the flow's write?
            ExecTrace.note('Flow_Stamp__c as seen by ' + tag + ' = ' + a.Flow_Stamp__c);

            a.Trigger_Stamp__c = (String.isBlank(a.Trigger_Stamp__c) ? '' : a.Trigger_Stamp__c + ' > ')
                               + tag + '@d' + ExecTrace.saveDepth;
        }
    }

    private static void observe(List<Account> accts) {
        for (Account a : accts) {
            ExecTrace.note('Id=' + a.Id
                         + ' | Flow=' + a.Flow_Stamp__c
                         + ' | Trigger=' + a.Trigger_Stamp__c
                         + ' | AfterFlow=' + a.After_Flow_Stamp__c);
        }
    }
}

That note() inside stamp() is the single most instructive line in the whole setup. If Flow_Stamp__c is already populated when the before trigger reads it, you've directly observed step 3 running before step 4.

*********************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Flow 1 — before-save (step 3)

Click path: Setup → Flows → New → Record-Triggered Flow → Account → A record is created or updated → Fast Field Updates (before save) → Assignment element → $Record.Flow_Stamp__c = BEFORE-SAVE-FLOW.

Metadata if you'd rather deploy it:

