Experiment 3 — the chunking bug
apex
List<Account> accts = new List<Account>();
for (Integer i = 0; i < 450; i++) {
    accts.add(new Account(Name = 'Bulk ' + i, Rating = 'Warm'));
}
insert accts;
### [1] BEFORE_INSERT | depth=1 | rows=200
### [2] AFTER_INSERT  | depth=1 | rows=200
### [3] BEFORE_INSERT | depth=1 | rows=200
### [4] AFTER_INSERT  | depth=1 | rows=200
### [5] BEFORE_INSERT | depth=1 | rows=50
### [6] AFTER_INSERT  | depth=1 | rows=50

Three invocations, depth=1 every time. This is the log that kills the naive static-boolean guard: a bare hasRun flag would set on invocation 1 and silently skip 250 records, and depth never rises because these aren't recursion — they're legitimate chunks.

