Gotchas that will waste your afternoon

Logs truncate silently. Any single log over 20 MB gets trimmed from the middle — you keep the head and tail and lose exactly the nesting you were trying to read. Drop Database and System to NONE when you only care about flow/trigger ordering, and test with 1–2 records rather than 450.

FINEST changes behavior. Log level FINEST on Apex Code adds real overhead and can push you over the 10-second CPU limit on transactions that pass fine at DEBUG. If a bulk operation only fails when you're logging, that's the cause.

System.debug always executes. Setting Apex Code to NONE suppresses the output, not the string concatenation. Heavy debug statements in a loop still burn CPU in production.

Only 24 hours of trace flag. Trace flags expire; re-enable before each session. And logs are capped at 1000 per user / 250 MB org-wide — after that new logs stop being generated until you delete old ones. If your log mysteriously doesn't appear, that's usually why.

Order among multiple flows on one object is not guaranteed unless you set Flow Trigger Order (the triggerOrder field, 1–2000) on each. Without it, two before-save flows on Account run in an undefined sequence — same hazard as multiple triggers per object.

Once you've watched experiment 3, the Set<Id>-based recursion guard from earlier stops being an abstract preference and becomes obvious. Good next step: instrument the guard itself with ExecTrace.note() so you can see it skip on the recursive pass but not on chunks 2 and 3.
